Here's the revised C# function using `ReadOnlySpan<char>` to extract the n-th field from a string with a single character delimiter:

```csharp
public static class FieldExtractor
{
    public static ReadOnlySpan<char> GetField(ReadOnlySpan<char> input, int n, char delimiter)
    {
        int start = 0, end = 0;
        int count = 0;

        while (end < input.Length)
        {
            if (input[end] == delimiter)
            {
                if (count == n)
                {
                    return input.Slice(start, end - start);
                }
                count++;
                start = end + 1;
            }
            end++;
        }

        // Check for the last field after the loop
        if (count == n)
        {
            return input.Slice(start, end - start);
        }

        return ReadOnlySpan<char>.Empty; // Return empty span if not found
    }
}

// Usage
ReadOnlySpan<char> input = "123 abc def".AsSpan();
int n = 1; // Index starts at 0
char delimiter = ' ';
ReadOnlySpan<char> result = FieldExtractor.GetField(input, n, delimiter);
Console.WriteLine(result.ToString()); // Output: abc
```

This function now efficiently extracts fields using `ReadOnlySpan<char>`, ideal for performance-sensitive scenarios.

