Yes, it is possible to have a `constexpr` function within another `constexpr` function in C++. This allows you to organize your code into smaller, reusable pieces while still adhering to compile-time evaluation.

Here's a simple example demonstrating this:

```cpp
#include <array>

constexpr int inner_function(int x) {
    return x * x;
}

constexpr int outer_function(const std::array<int, 5>& arr) {
    int sum = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < arr.size(); ++i) {
        sum += inner_function(arr[i]);
    }
    return sum;
}

constexpr std::array<int, 5> values = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
constexpr int result = outer_function(values);
```

In this example:
